'''Sadio Mané''' (born 10 April 1992) is a Senegalese professional [[Football player|footballer]] who plays as a [[left winger]] for [[Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al Nassr FC|Al-Nassr]] and the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]]. He is widely regarded as one of the best wingers of his generation and one of the greatest African players of all time.{{efn |Attributed to multiple sources:<ref>{{cite news |date=22 July 2019 |title=50 Greatest African Players of All Time |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/07/22/50-greatest-african-players-all-time |newspaper=Sports Illustrated}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Fish |first=Hal |date=1 October 2024 |title=20 Greatest African Players in Football History Ranked |url=https://www.givemesport.com/greatest-african-players-football-soccer-history/ |access-date=1 October 2024 |website=GiveMeSport.com}}</ref><ref name="FFT" /><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Ben Hayward |date=28 November 2023 |title=Best wingers in football history |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/best-wingers-in-football-history |access-date=2024-11-22 |website=fourfourtwo.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Jacobs-Bryant |first1=Kerrie |last2=Jeevathayalan |first2=Vijievan |date=10 June 2025 |title=20 Greatest Left-Wingers in Football History [Ranked] |url=https://www.givemesport.com/greatest-left-wingers-football-soccer-history-ranked/ |access-date=19 October 2025 |website=GiveMeSport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=20 December 2019 |title=The 100 best male footballers in the world 2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/ng-interactive/2019/dec/17/the-100-best-male-footballers-in-the-world-2019 |access-date=18 June 2025 |website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Christenson |first=Marcus |date=24 December 2020 |title=The 100 best male footballers in the world 2020 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2020/dec/21/the-100-best-male-footballers-in-the-world-2020 |access-date=18 June 2025 |website=The Guardian}}</ref>}}

Mané began his professional career with [[Ligue 2]] club [[FC Metz|Metz]] at the age of 19, but he departed after a solitary season to join Austrian club [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in 2012 for a fee of €4&nbsp;million, winning a [[Austrian Football Bundesliga|league]] and [[Austrian Cup|cup]] domestic double in the [[2013–14 FC Red Bull Salzburg season|2013–14 season]]. Later that summer, Mané transferred to English club [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for a club record fee of £11.8&nbsp;million. There, he set a new [[Premier League]] [[Premier League records and statistics|record]] for the fastest [[List of Premier League hat-tricks|hat-trick]], scored in 176 seconds in a 6–1 win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 2015.

Mané signed for fellow Premier League club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2016, for a reported fee of £34 million, making him the most expensive African player in history at that time.<ref name=BBC36642523>{{cite web|title=Sadio Mané: Liverpool complete £34m signing of Southampton forward|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36642523|website=BBC Sport|access-date=28 June 2016|date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Eight things about the Premier League Africans|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37255038|agency=BBC News|date=4 September 2016}}</ref> Having formed a formidable attacking trio with [[Mohamed Salah]] and [[Roberto Firmino]] after the departure of prolific midfielder [[Philippe Coutinho]], he helped the side reach back-to-back [[List of European Cup and UEFA Champions League finals|UEFA Champions League final]]s in [[2018 UEFA Champions League final|2018]] and [[2019 UEFA Champions League final|2019]], winning the latter. He also finished as the league's joint-top goalscorer in the [[2018–19 Premier League|2018–19 season]], winning the [[Premier League Golden Boot]]. Mané then helped end Liverpool's [[2019–20 Liverpool F.C. season|30-year league title drought]] by winning the [[2019–20 Premier League]]. In October 2021, he scored his [[List of footballers with 100 or more Premier League goals|100th Premier League goal]], becoming the third African to reach the landmark. Mané finished fourth and second in the [[2019 Ballon d'Or|2019]] and [[2022 Ballon d'Or|2022]] editions of the [[Ballon d'Or]], respectively; and in [[The Best FIFA Men's Player]] he ranked fifth in [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2019#The Best FIFA Men's Player|2019]] and fourth in [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2020#The Best FIFA Men's Player|2020]].
	
At international level, Mané has registered 55 goals in 127 [[Cap (association football)|appearances]] for Senegal since his debut in 2012, and currently ranks as his nation's [[Senegal national football team#Player records|all-time top goalscorer, and second in all-time appearances]].<ref name="RSSSF"/> He represented [[Senegal at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Senegal]] at the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2012 Olympics]], as well as the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]], [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|2017]], [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|2019]], [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations|2021]], [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]] and [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|2025]] editions of the [[Africa Cup of Nations]]. In the 2019 tournament, Mané helped Senegal to a runners-up finish, and a year later, was named [[African Footballer of the Year]]. In the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations Final#Details|2021 final]], Mané scored the winning kick in the penalty shoot-out to give Senegal their first Africa Cup of Nations title and he was also named the Player of the tournament. In 2022, he was crowned African Player of the Year for the second time. Mané also represented his nation at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], in its second-ever appearance in the competition. Mané later led Senegal to a third AFCON final in [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|2025]], once again being named the tournament's best player.

==Early life==
{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote= "''When I was young my dad was always saying how proud he was of me.. he was a man with a big heart. When he died, it had a big impact on me and the rest of my family.'' '''I said to myself''': '''Now I have to do my best to help my mother.''' ''That's a hard thing to deal with when you are so young.''" |source = — ''Mané on the impact his father's death had on him.''<ref name="theguardian"/>}}

Mané was born to [[Guineans|Guinean]] parents<ref>{{cite web|access-date=13 October 2023|date=13 October 2023|language=fr|title=Sadio Mané aurait donc pu jouer pour la Guinée ?|url=https://espacefootguinee.com/2023/10/13/sadio-mane-aurait-donc-pu-jouer-pour-la-guinee/|website=www.espacefootguinee.com}}<!-- auto-translated by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> in [[Bambali, Senegal|Bambali]], [[Sédhiou Department|Sédhiou]], [[Senegal]].<ref name="theguardian"/> He grew up in a religious household.<ref>{{Cite web |title=sportsdunia |date=4 May 2024 |url=https://www.sportsdunia.com/news/sadio-mane-early-life-clubs-family-net-worth-career-stats }}</ref> He wished for a career in football, but his father (who was an [[imam]]) forbade him from playing the sport as a child.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sadio Mané révèle que son père lui interdisait de jouer au foot|trans-title=Sadio Mané reveals that his father forbade him from playing football |url=https://rmcsport.bfmtv.com/football/video-sadio-mane-revele-que-son-pere-lui-interdisait-de-jouer-au-foot_AN-201712030126.html |publisher=RMC Sport News|access-date=30 April 2018|date=3 December 2017|language=fr}}</ref> His father wanted him to prioritize his religious studies,<ref>{{Cite web |title=The rise of Sadio Mane |url=https://www.nordensa.com/the-rise-of-sadio-mane |access-date=2024-10-27 |website=Nordensa |language=en-US}}</ref> however, his father died when he was seven years old. At the age of 15, he ran away from his home village with the help of a childhood friend, Luc Djiboune, and went to [[Dakar]] to pursue his ambition of becoming a footballer; from that time he was supported by his family to fulfill his potential.<ref name="theguardian"/>

==Club career==
===Early career===
In 2009, when playing in [[M'Bour]], he was spotted by scouts and later referred to [[Génération Foot]], a club that he helped attain promotion to the second division in the 2010–11 season.<ref name="theguardian">{{cite web |last=Aarons |first=Ed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/apr/08/sadio-mane-documentary-made-in-senegal-liverpool |title=Sadio Mané: 'I wanted to build a hospital to give people hope' |work=The Guardian |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=17 June 2022}}</ref><ref name="ledauphine">{{cite web |url=https://www.ledauphine.com/sport/2018/06/19/senegal-sadio-mane-l-ascension-qui-fait-rever |title=Sénégal: Sadio Mané, l'ascension qui fait rêver |work=[[Le Dauphiné libéré]] |language=fr |date=19 June 2018 |access-date=17 June 2022}}</ref>

===Metz===
In 2011, Mané joined [[FC Metz|Metz]] which had a partnership with Génération Foot.<ref name="ledauphine"/> He made his professional debut on 14 January 2012, coming on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Kévin Diaz (footballer born 1988)|Kévin Diaz]] in the 75th minute of a 0–1 home defeat against [[SC Bastia|Bastia]] in [[Ligue 2]].<ref name="FFT">{{cite web |last=Ratcliffe |first=Alison |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/sadio-mane-liverpool-senegal-african-footballer-year-hospital-school-champions-league-jurgen-klopp |title=The journey of Liverpool's Sadio Mane to become one of the world's best footballers |date=6 February 2022 |access-date=17 June 2022 |work=[[FourFourTwo]]}}</ref> He made 19 appearances in [[2011–12 Ligue 2|his first league season]], 12 as a starter, and scored a solitary goal in a 2–5 loss to [[EA Guingamp|Guingamp]] at the [[Stade Saint-Symphorien]] on 4 May.<ref name="FFT"/> Metz was [[relegated]] to the [[Championnat National]] at the end of the season.

===Red Bull Salzburg===
[[File:RBS gegen Metz59.JPG|thumb|Mané (right) playing for [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in 2013]]

Metz set an asking price of €2&nbsp;million for Mané, and he attracted attention, including from [[Austrian Football Bundesliga|Austrian Bundesliga]] side [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] sporting director [[Ralf Rangnick]].<ref name="FFT"/> Having received several offers throughout the summer, Metz upped their asking price to €4&nbsp;million,<ref name="FFT"/> and he moved to Salzburg on 31 August 2012, the third-biggest transfer fee that Metz had ever received.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sadio Mané transféré au Red Bull Salzburg|trans-title=Sadio Mané transferred to Red Bull Salzburg|url=http://www.fcmetz.com/article/Transfert/2012-08-31-17-25-55_sadio-mane-transfere-au-red-bull-salzburg.html |publisher=FC Metz |access-date=2 September 2014|language=fr|date=31 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103230754/http://www.fcmetz.com/article/Transfert/2012-08-31-17-25-55_sadio-mane-transfere-au-red-bull-salzburg.html|archive-date=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Die Bullen im Kaufrausch|trans-title=The Bulls on a spending spree|url=http://www.news.at/a/red-bull-salzburg-die-bullen-kaufrausch-340805|website=news.at |access-date=2 September 2014|language=de|date=31 August 2014}}</ref>

He scored his first [[hat-trick]] for the club on 31 October, in a 3–1 away win at SC Kalsdorf in the third round of the [[Austrian Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kalsdorf 1–3 Salzburg|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ie/match/kalsdorf-vs-salzburg/1397693/lineups|website=Goal.com|access-date=23 February 2015}}</ref>

On 27 October 2013, he netted his first hat-trick in the Austrian Bundesliga, during a 3–0 win away to [[SV Grödig|Grödig]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Grödig 0–3 Salzburg |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/gr%C3%B6dig-vs-salzburg/1487388/preview|website=Goal.com|access-date=23 February 2015}}</ref> He scored another treble on 7 May 2014 as Salzburg won 7–0 at [[SV Horn|Horn]] in the cup semi-finals;<ref>{{cite news|title=Red Bulls in cup final after goal fest!|url=http://www.redbulls.com/en/fc-red-bull-salzburg/news/saison_2013_14/red-bulls-in-cup-final-after-goal-fest.html|access-date=23 February 2015|publisher=FC Red Bull Salzburg|date=7 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223024239/http://www.redbulls.com/en/fc-red-bull-salzburg/news/saison_2013_14/red-bulls-in-cup-final-after-goal-fest.html |archive-date=23 February 2015}}</ref> the season ended with the team winning a domestic [[Double (association football)|double]]. At the end of August 2014 Mané forced a transfer out of the club, by not coming to the training and to the most important game for Salzburg at that time to qualify for the Champions League.<ref>[http://www.weltfussball.at/news/_n1232661_/skandal-um-sadio-mane-vor-malmoe-spiel/ Skandal um Sadio Mané vor Malmö-Spiel], weltfussball.at, 26 August 2014</ref>

===Southampton===
====2014–15 season====
On 1 September 2014, Mané transferred to [[Premier League]] side [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for £11.8&nbsp;million, signing a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Southampton sign £10m forward Sadio Mané & Toby Alderweireld |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29025087 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=3 September 2014|date=2 September 2014}}</ref> He made his debut 22 days later in a 2–1 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], winning the penalty for Southampton's first goal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal 1–2 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29216769 |work=BBC Sport |date=23 September 2014 |access-date=23 September 2014}}</ref> He made his first league appearance for the club in another 2–1 victory over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] on 27 September, starting and assisting [[Ryan Bertrand]] for the first goal of the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29289926|title=Southampton 2–1 Queens Park Rangers|work=BBC Sport|date=27 September 2014|access-date=27 September 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in an 8–0 victory over [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 18 October,<ref>{{cite web |last=Reddy |first=Luke |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29580147 |title=Southampton 8–0 Sunderland |work=BBC Sport |date=18 October 2014 |access-date=18 October 2014}}</ref> although this was subsequently credited as an own goal by [[Patrick van Aanholt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Southampton 8 – 0 Sunderland |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/matchday/matches/2014-2015/epl.match-stats.html/southampton-vs-sunderland |publisher=Premier League |access-date=24 October 2014 |date=18 October 2014 |archive-date=2 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150902121522/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/matchday/matches/2014-2015/epl.match-stats.html/southampton-vs-sunderland }}</ref> He did, however, score his first goal in his next game, a 1–0 win over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] a week later.<ref>{{cite web |last=Canavan |first=Steve |title=Southampton 1–0 Stoke |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29670448 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 October 2014|date=25 October 2014}}</ref>

In December and January he scored in three successive matches, against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30544147 |title=Crystal Palace 1–3 Southampton |work=BBC Sport |date=26 December 2014 |access-date=2 January 2015}}</ref> [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30566736 |title=Southampton 1–1 Chelsea |work=BBC Sport |date=28 December 2014 |access-date=2 January 2015}}</ref> and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30600817 |title=Southampton 2–0 Arsenal |website=BBC Sport |date=1 January 2015 |access-date=2 January 2015}}</ref> Mané scored two late winning goals in 1–0 league victories at [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] on 7 February 2015 and at home to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 3 March respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31071178 |title=QPR 0–1 Southampton |work=BBC Sport |date=7 February 2015 |access-date=6 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31598153 |title=Southampton 1–0 Crystal Palace |work=BBC Sport |date=3 March 2015 |access-date=6 August 2015}}</ref> However, Mané had been dropped from Southampton's starting line-up for their 0–2 home defeat to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 22 February as a punishment for being late to the stadium.<ref>{{cite news |title=Southampton: Sadio Mané dropped for being late – Koeman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31579123 |access-date=22 February 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=22 February 2015}}</ref>

On 16 May, during Southampton's final home match of the season, Mané scored three times in 2 minutes 56 seconds in a 6–1 win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] to set a new [[Premier League records and statistics|Premier League record]] for the fastest [[hat-trick]]. The record had been held since 1994 by [[Robbie Fowler]], who scored three against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 4 minutes and 33 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/may/16/southampton-aston-villa-premier-league-match-report|title=Southampton's Sadio Mané hits record hat-trick to rout Aston Villa|date=16 May 2015|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> Mané finished the season with 10 goals from 32 appearances in all competitions.

====2015–16 season====
[[File:Audi- quattro-Cup 23.JPG|thumb|Mané (right) playing for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 2015]]
Mané began the [[2015–16 Southampton F.C. season|2015–16 season]] by registering two assists in the [[2015–16 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] third qualifying round first leg match with [[Vitesse Arnhem]] at home and scoring in the return leg, as Southampton eased through to the next round 5–0 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33667103 |title=Southampton 3–0 Vitesse Arnhem |work=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2015 |access-date=6 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33738509 |title=Vitesse Arnhem 0–2 Southampton |work=BBC Sport |date=6 August 2015 |access-date=6 August 2015}}</ref> On 2 December, he took 39 seconds to open the scoring against Liverpool in the quarter-finals of the League Cup, but the Saints eventually lost 6–1 at home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Southampton 1–6 Liverpool |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34918281 |access-date=2 December 2015 |work=BBC Sport |date=2 December 2015}}</ref>

On 2 January 2016, he was again dropped from the starting line-up by manager [[Ronald Koeman]] for a match at [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] when he turned up late for a pre-match meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sadio Mané: Southampton midfielder dropped for being late |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35214588 |access-date=3 January 2016 |work=BBC Sport |date=2 January 2016}}</ref> He received a straight red card on 12 March at the end of a 2–1 win at [[Stoke City]] for a collision into [[Erik Pieters]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Sharpe |first=Rich |title=Stoke City 1 Southampton 2: Ronald Koeman says his side will appeal against Sadio Mané's red card |url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-1-Southampton-2-Ronald-Koeman-says/story-28913551-detail/story.html |access-date=13 March 2016 |newspaper=The Sentinel |date=13 March 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=June 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> although this was quickly overturned on appeal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Southampton win appeal against Sadio Mané red card|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35803664|work=BBC Sport|access-date=15 March 2016|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sadio Mané's claim against red card upheld by Commission|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/governance/2016/mar/sadio-mane-southampton-red-card-appeal-upheld|publisher=The FA |access-date=15 March 2016|date=15 March 2016}}</ref>

Having failed to score in the league for over four months, Mané scored twice in a 3–2 victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 20 March 2016,<ref>{{cite web |last=Henson |first=Mike |title=Southampton 3 Liverpool 2 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35796778 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2 May 2016|date=20 March 2016}}</ref> followed by five goals in the next five matches, including a hat-trick in a 4–2 victory against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 1 May.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rich |first=James |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/may/01/southampton-manchester-city-premier-league-match-report |title=Southampton's Sadio Mané in hat-trick romp against Manchester City |access-date=2 May 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 May 2016}}</ref> He finished the season as Southampton's top scorer, with 15 goals in all competitions.{{citation needed|date= October 2023}}

===Liverpool===
====2016–17 season====
[[File:Liver-SM 2017 (11 cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Mané playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2017]]
On 28 June 2016, Mané joined [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for a transfer fee of £34&nbsp;million (which could rise to £36&nbsp;million) on a five-year contract. The transfer fee made him the most expensive African player in history at the time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36642523 |title=Sadio Mané: Liverpool complete £34m signing of Southampton forward |website=BBC Sport|access-date=28 June 2016|date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/10326309/sadio-mane-has-medical-as-liverpool-agree-transfer-fee-of-16334m-with-southampton |title=Sadio Mane has medical as Liverpool agree transfer fee of £34m with Southampton|date=28 June 2016|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> On 14 August, he made his [[Premier League]] debut for the Reds, scoring the fourth goal in a 4–3 away win against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chowdhury|first1=Saj|title=Liverpool held on to beat Arsenal in a stunning Premier League opening-weekend encounter at Emirates Stadium.|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37001073|access-date=14 August 2016 |website=BBC Sport|date=14 August 2016}}</ref> Having missed Liverpool's defeat at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] through a slight shoulder injury, Mané returned to the starting line-up against [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] in the [[2016–17 EFL Cup|League Cup]] where he had two assists in a 5–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=Liverpool hit five to see of Burton in EFL Cup |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/232883-liverpool-hit-five-to-see-off-burton-in-efl-cup|access-date=23 August 2016|publisher=Liverpool F.C.|date=23 August 2016}}</ref>

On 19 December, Mané scored the only goal of the 227th [[Merseyside derby]] in added time against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/dec/19/everton-liverpool-premier-league-match-report|title=Sadio Mané's injury-time winner earns Liverpool dramatic derby victory|date=19 December 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=21 December 2016}}</ref>
On 11 February 2017, Mané scored two goals within two minutes against [[Tottenham Hotspur]] at Anfield, for Liverpool's first league win in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/feb/11/liverpool-tottenham-hotspur-premier-league-match-report|title=Liverpool's Sadio Mané fires quickfire double to stun Tottenham|first=Paul |last=Wilson|newspaper=The Guardian|date=11 February 2017|access-date=12 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/02/11/liverpool-vs-tottenham-premier-league-live-score/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/02/11/liverpool-vs-tottenham-premier-league-live-score/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Liverpool 2 Tottenham 0: Sadio Mané scores twice as Reds record first league win of 2017|first1=Sam |last1=Wallace|first2=JJ |last2=Bull|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=12 February 2017|access-date=12 February 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref> On 20 April 2017, Mané was named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] after scoring 13 league goals in his first season with Liverpool.<ref name=PFA1617>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39648483 |title=PFA teams of the year: Chelsea and Tottenham dominate Premier League XI |website=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2017 |access-date=6 May 2018}}</ref> Despite missing the latter part of the campaign through injury, Mané was awarded the Liverpool [[Liverpool F.C.#Player of the season|Player of the Season]] award on 9 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Chris|title=Sadio Mané takes top prizes at LFC Players' Awards|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/262799-sadio-mane-takes-top-prizes-at-lfc-players-awards|publisher=Liverpool F.C.|access-date=10 May 2017|date=9 May 2017}}</ref>

====2017–18 season====
In the first match of the new season, on 12 August 2017, away to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], Mané scored Liverpool's first goal of the season in a 3–3 draw. He was named [[Premier League Player of the Month]] after scoring a goal in each of the Reds' three matches in August.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frankland|first1=Josh|title=Liverpool's Sadio Mané wins August's Premier League Player of the Month award|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/11025598/liverpools-sadio-mane-wins-augusts-premier-league-player-of-the-month-award|access-date=8 September 2017|website=Sky Sports|date=8 September 2017}}</ref> On 9 September 2017, he was given a straight red card in the first half of a 5–0 loss to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] for a high boot against goalkeeper [[Ederson Moraes|Ederson]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ogden|first1=Mark|title=Man City ease past Liverpool after Mane sees red for Ederson challenge|url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/the-match/60/post/3199105/man-city-ease-past-liverpool-after-sadio-mane-sees-red-for-ederson-challenge|access-date=9 September 2017|website=ESPN FC |date=9 September 2017}}</ref> resulting in a three-match ban.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sadio Mané: Liverpool lose appeal against length of ban for red card|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41232863|website=BBC Sport|access-date=22 September 2017|date=12 September 2017}}</ref> Mané, [[Mohamed Salah]], [[Roberto Firmino]] and [[Philippe Coutinho]] made up a prolific attacking quartet dubbed the "Fab Four" and "Fab Three" after the mid-season exit of the latter.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burton|first1=Chris|title=Klopp sees Mané mojo back as part of Liverpool's 'Fab Three'|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/klopp-sees-mane-mojo-back-as-part-of-liverpools-fab-three/1mzi60n72yhyr1f4yt92n0oku1|access-date=22 April 2018|publisher=Goal.com|date=20 February 2018}}</ref>

On 14 February 2018, Mané scored his first [[List of UEFA Champions League hat-tricks|hat-trick]] for Liverpool in a 5–0 away win against [[FC Porto|Porto]] in the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|round of 16]] first leg of the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/feb/14/sadio-mane-liverpool-jurgen-klopp-porto-champions-league|title=Sadio Mané is Liverpool's comeback king with hat-trick, says Jürgen Klopp|date=14 February 2018|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=15 February 2018}}</ref> In doing so, he became only the second player to score an away hat-trick for the club in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/332404-liverpool-2018-review|title=Records, special nights and new stars – the story of Liverpool's 2018|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Flemming|first=Scott|date=1 January 2019|access-date=1 January 2019}}</ref> Later, with a goal in the 3–0 win over [[AFC Bournemouth]] on 14 April, he overtook [[Demba Ba]]'s record of 43 to become the highest scoring Senegalese in Premier League history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mané makes Premier League history with latest Liverpool goal|url=http://www.goal.com/en-om/news/mane-makes-premier-league-history-with-latest-liverpool-goal/l41g5m3n7cwy1xk09e1ljeh2y|access-date=22 April 2018|website=Goal.com|date=14 April 2018}}</ref>

On 26 May, during the [[2018 UEFA Champions League final]] against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], Mané scored Liverpool's equalising goal in a 3–1 defeat.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Avi Creditor |title=LIVE: Benzema Blocks Karius Throw for Bizarre Opener, Mané Answers in UCL Final |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/05/26/real-madrid-liverpool-champions-league-final-goals-video-salah-mane-ronaldo-isco |date=26 May 2018 |access-date=26 May 2018 |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] }}</ref> In doing so, he became the first Senegalese player to score in the final of the competition. His goal was also his 10th for the campaign which saw Liverpool become the first team in history to have three players score 10+ goals in a single Champions League season, with Mané achieving the milestone alongside fellow [[Forward (association football)|forwards]] Salah and Firmino.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/mane-makes-champions-league-history-for-liverpools-fab-three/1igcjwc8w03114w064vd49r2x|title=Mané makes Champions League history for Liverpool's 'Fab Three'|website=Goal.com|last=Burton|first=Chris|date=26 May 2018|access-date=27 May 2018}}</ref>

====2018–19 season====
On 22 November 2018, Mané signed a new long-term deal with Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sadio Mané: Senegal forward agrees new long-term Liverpool deal |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46310219 |website=BBC Sport |date=22 November 2018}}</ref> On 10 March 2019, Mané scored twice in a 4–2 win over Burnley, the second of which was his 50th competitive goal for Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/mar/10/liverpool-burnley-premier-league-match-report|title=Liverpool 4–2 Burnley|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.in/football/english-premier-league/23/blog/post/3794114/liverpool-buoyed-by-mane-9-10-and-firmino-8-10-to-beat-burnley|title=Mané scores his 50th goal for Liverpool|publisher=ESPN|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref> His goals also saw him become only the fifth Liverpool player to score in six consecutive home Premier League appearances after [[Michael Owen]], [[Fernando Torres]], [[Luis Suárez]] and Salah.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-za/news/sadio-mane-reaches-liverpool-milestone-with-brace-against/17liiwuwg88ox1v3sldcstg5jw|title=Sadio Mané reaches Liverpool milestone with brace against Burnley|website=Goal.com|last=Taiwo|first=Taiye|date=11 March 2019|access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref> Three days later, he scored twice more in a 3–1 win over [[Bayern Munich]] to help Liverpool progress to the quarter-finals of the Champions League. In doing so, he became the club's record goalscorer away from home in the competition with seven goals to his name.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47564339|title=Champions League last 16: Best of the stats in Europe|website=BBC Sport|date=14 February 2019|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> During Liverpool's next match, he broke another of Ba's records to become the Senegalese player with the most goals scored in a single Premier League season, after scoring his 17th goal for the campaign in a 2–1 win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-za/news/mane-breaks-premier-league-record-as-liverpool-hot-streak/12alut43syok81uliikiiqmosf|title=Mané breaks Premier League record as Liverpool hot streak continues|website=Goal.com|last=Storer|first=Tom|date=17 March 2019|access-date=28 March 2019}}</ref> On 20 April, he was one of six players nominated for the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] award alongside teammate [[Virgil van Dijk]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/20/pfa-player-yearvirgil-van-dijk-raheem-sterling-lead-way-six/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/20/pfa-player-yearvirgil-van-dijk-raheem-sterling-lead-way-six/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=PFA Player of the Year: Virgil van Dijk and Raheem Sterling lead the way in six-man shortlist|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=20 April 2019|access-date=20 April 2019}}{{cbignore}}</ref> He was also named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] alongside Liverpool teammates, [[Trent Alexander-Arnold]], [[Andrew Robertson]] and Van Dijk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2019/4/25/premier-league-team-of-the-year|title=PFA Premier League Team of the Year|publisher=Professional Footballers' Association|date=25 April 2019|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref>

{{Quote box
| width = 30%
| align = left
| quote = "What makes him special is that he never stops believing… in the meeting before the game he was really convinced that we could do it. Even though we were missing two of the best players in the world [Salah and Roberto Firmino]. He pushed the boys hard to give everything possible and tried to take the pressure off us."
| source = — Mané on the impact his manager [[Jürgen Klopp]] had on him and the whole Liverpool squad to inspire them to a famous Champions League comeback against Barcelona in the semi-finals.<ref name="theguardian"/>
}}

On the final day of the domestic campaign, Mané scored twice in a 2–0 win over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]. His brace took him to 22 goals for the campaign which saw him share the [[Premier League Golden Boot]] award with Salah and Arsenal's [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/349839-mohamed-salah-sadio-mane-premier-league-golden-boot|title=Sadio Mane and Mohamed Salah win Premier League Golden Boot|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Williams|first=Sam|date=12 May 2019|access-date=13 May 2019}}</ref> On 1 June, Mané helped win an early penalty for Liverpool in the [[2019 UEFA Champions League final]] against Tottenham, only 24 seconds after the kick-off, after his cross was judged to have hit [[Moussa Sissoko]]'s arm inside the penalty area; Salah subsequently converted from the spot to open the scoring, and Liverpool ultimately won the match 2–0 to claim the title.<ref name="2018–19UCL"/>

==== 2019–20 season ====
[[File:Liverpool vs. Chelsea, UEFA Super Cup 2019-08-14 53.jpg|thumb|left|Mané lifting the UEFA Super Cup after scoring twice against Chelsea in the final.]]

[[File:FC Salzburg gegen Liverpool FC (UEFA Champions League 10.Dezember 2019) 52.jpg|180px|thumb|Mané playing for Liverpool in the UEFA Champions League, during December 2019]]
On 14 August 2019, Mané scored twice in the [[2019 UEFA Super Cup]] final against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in a match that Liverpool won 5–4 on penalties after the game had finished 2–2 after 120 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adrian the hero as Liverpool beat Chelsea on penalties to win Super Cup |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49332825 |access-date=14 August 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mané was named man of the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/news/0254-0d417f66c528-e5b666e344ce-1000--liverpool-beat-chelsea-on-penalties-to-win-super-cup/ |title=Liverpool beat Chelsea on penalties to win Super Cup |publisher=UEFA |date=14 August 2018 |access-date=14 August 2018}}</ref> Exactly one month later, he scored twice in a 3–1 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and extended his record run of matches without defeat for Liverpool at [[Anfield]] to 50 matches, a league record by any player at a particular stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/364571-sadio-mane-reaches-unbeaten-premier-league-landmark-at-anfield|title=Sadio Mane reaches unbeaten Premier League landmark at Anfield|publisher=Liverpool F.C.|last=Shaw|first=Chris|date=14 September 2019|access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref> On his 100th Premier League appearance for Liverpool on 5 October, Mané scored his 50th league goal for the club in a 2–1 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/367859-liverpool-leicester-premier-league-talking-points|title=Liverpool 2–1 Leicester: Five talking points|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last=Price|first=Glenn|date=5 October 2019|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>

On 21 October, Mané was named in the 30-man shortlist for the [[2019 Ballon d'Or]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sen.com.au/news/2019/10/21/30-man-shortlist-for-2019-ballon-dor-announced/|title=30-man shortlist for 2019 Ballon d'Or announced|access-date=21 October 2019|website=sen}}</ref> On 2 December he finished in fourth place for the award, behind [[Lionel Messi]], Liverpool teammate [[Virgil van Dijk]] and [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref>{{cite news |date=2 December 2019 |title=Lionel Messi remporte le Ballon d'Or France Football pour la sixième fois de l'histoire |language=fr |trans-title=Lionel Messi wins the France Football Ballon d'Or for the sixth time in history |website=France Football |url=https://www.francefootball.fr/news/Lionel-messi-remporte-le-ballon-d-or-france-football-pour-la-sixieme-fois-de-l-histoire/1085998 |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Two days later, he scored once and assisted two more goals as Liverpool beat Everton 5–2 in the Merseyside derby to extend their unbeaten run in league football to 32 matches, which was a new club record.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/12/04/liverpool-vs-everton-premier-league-live-score-latest-updates/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/12/04/liverpool-vs-everton-premier-league-live-score-latest-updates/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Liverpool put five past Everton for new unbeaten club record as Marco Silva teeters on the brink after derby defeat
|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=4 December 2019|access-date=6 December 2019|last=Bascombe|first=Chris}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Later that month, Liverpool won the [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup]], with Mané setting up the winning goal scored by Firmino in the [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup final|final]] against [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Firmino winner seals Club World Cup win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50869633?isBumped=0&postFreq=0&isEmpty=0&isProfane=0&tooLong=0&charCount=0&isAwaitingProcessPreMod=0&isSubmitted=1&filter=none&initial_page_size=10&postId=137711507 |access-date=21 December 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 7 January 2020, Mané was named the CAF [[African Footballer of the Year]].<ref name=Guardian070120>{{cite news |last=Aarons |first=Ed |title=Liverpool's Sadio Mané named African Footballer of the Year for first time |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/jan/07/liverpools-sadio-mane-named-african-footballer-of-the-year-for-first-time |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 January 2020 |access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Andrews |first=Patrick |title=Sadio Mané new king of Africa |url=https://football-news24.com/news/sadio-mane-new-king-of-africa/ |website=football-news24.com |date=8 January 2020 |access-date=8 January 2020}}</ref> He is only the second Senegalese (after [[El Hadji Diouf]]) to have won this award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/sports/2020/1/7/sadio-mane-has-been-named-the-2019-african-player-of-the-year|title=Sadio Mané has been named the 2019 African Player of the Year|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=7 January 2020|access-date=8 January 2020}}</ref>

On 24 February, Mané scored the winner in a 3–2 home win against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in the Premier League as Liverpool made it 21 consecutive home wins, a league record shared with [[Bill Shankly]]'s Liverpool team from 1972, and also made it a joint Premier League record 18 wins in a row.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/liverpool-equal-premier-league-winning-run-record-a4370351.html|title=Liverpool equal Premier League winning run record with victory over West Ham|access-date=24 February 2020|date=24 February 2020|newspaper=Evening Standard|first=Malik|last=Ouzia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Which Premier League records can Liverpool break? |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1561869 |access-date=25 February 2020 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref> On 7 March, Mané scored the winning goal in a 2–1 win against Bournemouth at Anfield as Liverpool set a new [[Football records and statistics in England#Wins|English top-flight record]] of 22 consecutive home wins.<ref>{{cite news |title=Salah and Milner reaction: 'We showed our mentality to win' |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/389748-salah-milner-liverpool-mentality-bournemouth-reaction |access-date=7 March 2020 |publisher=Liverpool F.C.}}</ref> Liverpool went on to win the Premier League title at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 June 2020|title=Liverpool confirmed as Premier League champions|url=http://www.premierleague.com/news/1697247|access-date=5 February 2021|website=www.premierleague.com}}</ref>

==== 2020–21 season====
On 20 September 2020, Mané opened his scoring account in the [[2020–21 Premier League]] with both Liverpool goals in a 2–0 win away to Chelsea.<ref>{{Cite news|title= Chelsea 0 Liverpool 2 |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54135434|access-date=20 September 2020}}</ref> On 2 October 2020, Mané tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sadio Mane tests positive for COVID-19|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/411091-sadio-mane-tests-positive-for-covid-19|date=2 October 2020|website=Liverpool FC}}</ref> Given his and Liverpool's stuttering form, Mané stated that 2020–21 had been the worst season of his career.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Liverpool's Sadio Mané admits to enduring 'worst season of my career' |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/may/11/liverpools-sadio-mane-admits-to-enduring-worst-season-of-my-career |date= 11 May 2021 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> On 23 May 2021, the final day of the League season, Mané scored a brace in a 2–0 win over Crystal Palace securing third-place for Liverpool and qualification for the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|next Champions League season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/57132111 |title=Liverpool 2–0 Crystal Palace |website=BBC Sport |date=23 May 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Premier League hits and misses: Farewell Sergio Aguero, Liverpool's second chance, Arsenal's glimpse of future |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12314477/premier-league-hits-and-misses-farewell-sergio-aguero-liverpools-second-chance-arsenals-glimpse-of-future|date=24 May 2021 |website=SkySports}}</ref>

====2021–22 season====
[[File:Liverpool FC gegen 1. FSV Mainz 05 (Testspiel 23. Juli 2021) 05.jpg|thumb|upright|Mané and Salah during a pre-season game in 2021]]
On 18 September 2021, Mané scored his 100th Liverpool goal in a 3–0 home win against Crystal Palace in the Premier League.<ref name="Mané 100"/> The goal against Crystal Palace also saw Mané set a new Premier League record by becoming the first player to score in nine consecutive league games against the same opponent.<ref name="Mané 100">{{cite news |title=Mané scores 100th goal in Liverpool win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58525384 |access-date=18 September 2021 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 16 October, Mané scored his [[List of footballers with 100 or more Premier League goals|100th Premier League goal]]—becoming the third African to reach the landmark after [[Didier Drogba]] and Salah—with Liverpool's opening goal in the 5–0 win away to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sadio Mane: Liverpool winger reaches 100 Premier League goals to join Mohamed Salah in '100 Club' |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12432092/sadio-mane-liverpool-winger-reaches-100-premier-league-goals-to-join-mohamed-salah-in-100-club |access-date=16 October 2021 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Watford 0-5 Liverpool: Roberto Firmino hat-trick and Mohamed Salah scores another stunner|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58833884 |access-date=16 October 2021 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 10 April 2022, his 30th birthday, Mané scored Liverpool's equalising goal in a 2–2 away draw against Manchester City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-au/news/liverpool-s-mane-joins-rooney-in-hallowed-premier-league/bltae349183109ad807|title=Liverpool's Mane joins Rooney in hallowed Premier League ranks with Manchester City goal|date=11 April 2022|access-date=11 April 2022|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|author=Oludare, Shina}}</ref> Mané then followed this with two goals against the same opposition on 16 April at [[Wembley Stadium]] in a FA Cup semi-final, in a 3–2 win to help Liverpool reach their first [[FA Cup final]] since 2012, which they [[2022 FA Cup Final|eventually won]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester City 2 Liverpool 3|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61120882 |access-date=27 April 2022 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 3 May, he scored the winning goal in a 3–2 away victory over [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] semi-final, to secure his team's place in the [[2022 UEFA Champions League final|final]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Cunningham |first=Jack |date=4 May 2022 |title=ICONIC Liverpool star Sadio Mane equals incredible Frank Lampard stat in Champions League semi-final clash with goal in comeback win against Villarreal |url=https://talksport.com/football/1100380/liverpool-sadio-mane-equals-frank-lampard-champions-league-record/ |website=Talksport}}</ref> which Liverpool eventually lost 1–0 to Real Madrid.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=634861 |title=Real Madrid overcome Liverpool to clinch record 14th Champions League title |website=ESBN |date=28 May 2022 }}</ref> Liverpool narrowly missed out on the chance to achieve a historic quadruple, coming second in the [[2021–22 Premier League|Premier League]] and the 2021–22 UEFA Champions League but winning both the [[2021–22 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] and the [[2021–22 FA Cup|FA Cup]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dunn |first=Carrie |date=28 May 2022 |title=Liverpool's quadruple, treble chase is over: Reds settle for double in 2021-22 |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/uk/football/news/liverpool-quadruple-chase-2021-22-reds-man-united-treble/pmwqorelovih6pge6xnpv3av#:~:text=The%20Reds%20were%20battling%20on,making%20history%20with%20a%20quadruple. |access-date=2 June 2023 |website=Sporting News}}</ref>

=== Bayern Munich ===
On 22 June 2022, Mané joined [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on a contract with the German side until 30 June 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |date=22 June 2022 |title=FC Bayern sign Sadio Mané |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2022/06/fc-bayern-sign-sadio-mane |website=fcbayern.com}}</ref> The fee was reported to be €32 million (£27.4m) potentially rising to €41 million (£35m) based on appearances plus individual and team achievements.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Mane leaves Liverpool to join Bayern in £35m deal |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61877332 |access-date=22 June 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=22 June 2022 |title=Mane leaves Liverpool to join Bayern Munich |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/4689018/liverpools-sadio-mane-joins-bayern-munichending-trophy-filled-six-years-at-anfield |access-date=22 June 2022 |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> On 30 July 2022, Mané made his official debut, starting in the [[2022 DFL-Supercup]] and scored his debut goal to help Bayern to 5–3 victory over [[RB Leipzig]] at the [[Red Bull Arena (Leipzig)|Red Bull Arena]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=30 July 2022 |title=Mane scores first Bayern goal in Super Cup win |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62363061 |access-date=6 August 2022}}</ref> He followed this up a week later with his first Bundesliga goal in a 6–1 victory over [[Eintracht Frankfurt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eintracht Frankfurt 1 Bayern Munich 6 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62443884 |website=BBc Sport |access-date=6 August 2022 |date=5 August 2022}}</ref>

On 8 November, Mané suffered an injury and had to go off after 20 minutes of Bayern's 6–1 victory against [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bernstein |first=Dan |date=8 November 2022 |title='This part easily splinters' - Senegal star Sadio Mane injured with Bayern Munich just before World Cup |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/senegal-star-sadio-mane-injured-with-bayern-munich-just-before-world-cup/bltfe4c010e2947b4e2 |access-date=26 February 2023 |website=Goal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=8 November 2022 |title=Serge Gnabry hits hat-trick as Bayern Munich overpower Werder Bremen |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-werder-bremen-live-team-news-match-stats-mane-musiala-neuer-21801 |access-date=26 February 2023 |website=Bundesliga |language=en}}</ref> This injury prevented him from competing in the 2022 FIFA World Cup and he had to undergo surgery in his right fibula.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 November 2022 |title=Sadio Mané undergoes successful surgery |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2022/11/sadio-mane-undergoes-successful-surgery |access-date=26 February 2023 |website=Bayern Munich}}</ref> He stayed out for three months and made his return on 26 February 2023 as a substitute, coming on in the 65th minute for [[Kingsley Coman]] in Bayern's 3–0 win against [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 February 2023 |title=Sadio Mane makes Bayern Munich comeback |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/sadio-mane-injury-bayern-munich-update-comeback-senegal-21837 |access-date=26 February 2023 |website=Bundesliga |language=}}</ref>

On 13 April, Mané was suspended and fined by Bayern, following reports he punched teammate [[Leroy Sané]] in the dressing room after a 3–0 Champions League quarter-final loss to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65257844|title=Sadio Mane: Bayern Munich suspend forward after claims he punched Leroy Sane|website=BBC Sport|date=13 April 2023|access-date=13 April 2023}}</ref> On 28 May, Bayern Munich won the Bundesliga following the concession of two points by league leaders [[Borussia Dortmund]].''<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65714772 |title= 1. FC Köln 1 Bayern Munich 2|work= BBC Sport|access-date=29 May 2023}}</ref>''

===Al-Nassr===
[[File:(Tehran) Persepolis F.C. v Al Nassr FC, 19 September 2023 05.jpg|thumb|Mané (right) playing for [[Al Nassr FC|Al Nassr]] against [[Persepolis F.C.|Persepolis]] in September 2023 at the [[Azadi Stadium]]]]
On 1 August 2023, [[Saudi Professional League|Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al Nassr FC|Al Nassr]] announced the signing of Mané.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66378778|title=Sadio Mane leaves Bayern Munich to join Cristiano Ronaldo at Al-Nassr|website=BBC|date=1 August 2023|access-date=1 August 2023}}</ref> Mané later revealed that former Liverpool teammates [[Fabinho (footballer, born 1993)|Fabinho]] and [[Roberto Firmino]] had previously contacted him in order to recommend to him that he might join their clubs, [[Al-Ittihad Club (Jeddah)|Al-Ittihad]] and [[Al Ahli Saudi FC|Al-Ahli]] in Saudi Arabia respectively.<ref name="Recommendation">{{cite web |last=Davey |first=Lee |date=10 August 2023 |title=Sadio Mane reveals transfer pleas from two ex-Liverpool teammates before Saudi Arabia switch |url=https://talksport.com/football/1528003/sadio-mane-transfer-plea-liverpool-saudi-arabia/ |access-date=20 August 2023 |website=TalkSport}}</ref> Mané also stated that his former [[Captain (association football)|captain]] [[Jordan Henderson]] had sent him a good luck message upon his departure to Saudi Arabia.<ref name="Recommendation"/> Two days later, he made his debut replacing [[Abdulaziz Al-Aliwa]] at halftime in their 1–1 draw with [[Zamalek SC|Zamalek]] in the [[2023 Arab Club Champions Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=McAuley |first=John |date=4 August 2023 |title=Cristiano Ronaldo rescues Al Nassr's King Salman Cup bid as Sadio Mane makes debuts |url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/sport/football/2023/08/04/cristiano-ronaldo-rescues-al-nassrs-king-salman-cup-bid-as-sadio-mane-makes-debuts/ |access-date=4 August 2023 |website=The National}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 14 August in a 2–1 loss against [[Al-Ettifaq FC|Al-Ettifaq]] in the league.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.in/football/story/_/id/38192645/gerrard-al-ettifaq-beat-al-nassr-mane-opener|title=Gerrard's Al-Ettifaq beat Al Nassr in SPL opener despite Mane goal|date=15 August 2023|access-date=15 August 2023}}</ref>

==International career==
===2012–2017 ===
Mané was part of the [[Senegal national under-23 football team|Senegal team]] at the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2012 Olympic tournament]], and started every match as they advanced through [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament – Group A|Group A]] as runners-up to [[Great Britain national football team|Great Britain]] before losing 4–2 after extra time in the quarter-finals to eventual champions [[Mexico national under-23 football team|Mexico]].

Mané was ruled out of the [[Senegal national football team|Senegalese squad]] for the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations]] after suffering a calf injury in Southampton's 2–0 win against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 1 January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sadio Mané: Senegal midfielder to miss Africa Cup of Nations |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/30676190|access-date=5 January 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=4 January 2014}}</ref> He later returned to the squad, and started in their final two group matches against [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] and [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] in a [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations Group C|group stage exit]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Begley|first1=Emlyn|title=South Africa 1–1 Senegal|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/30843618|access-date=23 February 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hughes|first1=Ian|title=Senegal 0–2 Algeria|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30891881|access-date=23 February 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2015}}</ref>

===2017–2019===
Mané represented Senegal at the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Gabon and scored a goal in each of the nation's opening two games, 2–0 wins against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] and [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisanfield.com/2017/01/senegal-africa-cup-nations-quarter-finals-sadio-mane-scores/|title=Senegal through to Africa Cup of Nations quarter-finals as Sadio Mane scores again|website=This is Anfield|last=Lusby|first=Jack|date=20 January 2017|access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref> After a goalless draw in the quarter-final clash against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], he missed the penalty in the shoot-out that saw Senegal eliminated from the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jan/28/cameroon-senegal-sadio-mane-burkina-faso-tunisia-africa-cup-of-nations|title=Cameroon through to semi-finals after Senegal's Sadio Mané misses penalty|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 January 2017}}</ref>

In May 2018, Mané was named in Senegal's 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad – 23-man & preliminary lists & when will they be announced?|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|website=Goal.com|access-date=18 May 2018}}</ref> He scored the opening goal in a 2–2 draw against [[Japan national football team|Japan]] in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group H|group stage]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44439190|title=World Cup 2018: Japan come back twice against Senegal to draw 2–2|date=24 June 2018|website=BBC Sport|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref> Mané started all three of Senegal's group matches as they were eliminated after the first stage, finishing below Japan on fair play points.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/colombia-advance-to-last-16-senegal-eliminated|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709143025/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/colombia-advance-to-last-16-senegal-eliminated|archive-date=9 July 2018|title=Colombia advance to last 16, Senegal eliminated|date=28 June 2018|publisher=FIFA|access-date=28 June 2018}}</ref>
[[File:Finales CAN 2021 (13).jpg|thumb|Mané in action for [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] at the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]]]]
Mané was once again called up to Senegal's final squad for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingfut.com/2019/06/13/senegal-announce-strong-afcon-squad/ |title=Senegal announce strong AFCON squad |website=KingFut |date=13 June 2019 |access-date=23 June 2019}}</ref> He scored two goals and missed a penalty in a 3–0 win against [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]], as Senegal finished second in the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations Group C|group stage]] and qualified for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations knockout stage|knockout stage]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kenya 0–3 Senegal|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48740626|access-date=20 March 2020|website=BBC Sport|date=1 July 2019}}</ref> Mané scored the only goal of the match and missed another penalty in Senegal's 1–0 win over [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]] in the round of 16.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uganda 0–1 Senegal|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48795601|access-date=20 March 2020|website=BBC Sport|date=5 July 2019}}</ref> He played in Senegal's next three matches as they advanced to the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations final|final]], losing 1–0 to Algeria in a rematch of Senegal's opening game of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senegal 0–1 Algeria|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48959714|access-date=20 March 2020|website=BBC Sport|date=19 July 2019}}</ref> Despite finishing the competition as runner-up, Mané was named in the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations#CAF AFCON Team of the Tournament|Team of the Tournament]].<ref name="AFCON TOTY"/>

===2021–present ===
At the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]], Mané starred for Senegal as they won the competition for the first time. In the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations final|final]] against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] – a match which saw him go up against his Liverpool teammate [[Mohamed Salah]] – Mané saw his penalty saved in the 7th minute, but went on to score the winning kick in the penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sadio Mane named AFCON player of the tournament|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/sadio-mane-named-afcon-player-tournament|last=Williams|first=Sam|date=6 February 2022|access-date=7 February 2022|website=Liverpool FC}}</ref> As well as scoring the decisive kick to win the trophy, Mané scored three goals and had two assists prior to the final, and was named the player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Whitehead|first1=Jacob|last2=Bosher|first2=Luke|title=Sadio Mane named AFCON player of the tournament after Senegal triumph|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4182578/2022/02/07/sadio-mane-named-afcon-player-of-the-tournament-after-senegal-triumph/|date=7 February 2022|access-date=7 February 2022|website=The Athletic}}</ref> In the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF third round|third round of the 2022 World Cup qualifications]], he also scored the winning kick in the penalty shoot-out against Egypt after a 1–1 draw on aggregate, in order to qualify his country to the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/60881797 |title=World Cup 2022: Mane helps Senegal beat Egypt and qualify for Qatar after penalty shootout |website=BBC Sport |date=29 March 2022 }}</ref>

On 4 June 2022, Mané scored a hat-trick in a 3–1 win against [[Benin national football team|Benin]] in the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]], to become Senegal's all-time top scorer with 32 goals, surpassing [[Henri Camara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/61692468 |title=Sadio Mane shrugs off transfer talk in Senegal win in Nations Cup qualifier |website=BBC Sport |date=4 June 2022}}</ref>

On 11 November 2022, Mané was included in Senegal's 26-man squad for the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://allnews.ng/news/world-cup-2022-mane-makes-senegal-squad-for-qatar-full-list | title = World Cup 2022: Mane Makes Senegal Squad For Qatar [FULL LIST] | website = allnews.ng | date = 11 November 2022 | access-date = 11 November 2022 | first = Oladimeji | last = Balogun}}</ref> despite an injury he picked up during Bayern Munich's 6–1 win over [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] a few days prior.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://allnews.ng/news/sane-injury-not-too-bad-bayern-allay-senegals-fear | title = Mane Injury 'Not Too Bad' — Bayern Allay Senegal's Fear | website = allnews.ng | date = 9 November 2022 | access-date = 11 November 2022 | first = Oladimeji | last = Balogun}}</ref> However, on 17 November, Mané was ruled out of the tournament and withdrew from the squad.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63670760 |title=World Cup 2022: Senegal forward Sadio Mane ruled out with leg injury |work=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2022 |access-date=17 November 2022}}</ref>

Mané made his [[List of men's footballers with 100 or more international caps|100th appearance]] for Senegal on 18 November 2023, scoring twice in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifier]] against [[South Sudan national football team|South Sudan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67464850|title=World Cup 2026 qualifiers: Sadio Mane marks 100th cap for Senegal with a double|date=18 November 2023|website=BBC Sport Africa}}</ref>

In December 2023, Mané was named in Senegal's squad for the postponed [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]] held in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67840713|title=Afcon 2023: Senegal and Sadio Mane set for defence of title|date=29 December 2023|access-date=29 December 2023|work=BBC Sport Africa}}</ref> He ended the group stage with one goal against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] and assists against [[Gambia national football team|The Gambia]] and [[Guinea national football team|Guinea]]. He then played the full 120 minutes against the [[Côte d'Ivoire national football team|Ivory Coast]] in the round of 16, assisting [[Habib Diallo]] for Senegal's goal. After the match finished in a 1–1 draw after extra time, Senegal were knocked out by the hosts and eventual winners in the penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68052401|title=Afcon 2023: Senegal 1-1 Ivory Coast (aet, 4-5 on pens) - hosts oust holders on penalties|date=29 January 2024|access-date=28 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 14 October 2025, Mané netted twice in a 4–0 win against [[Mauritania national football team|Mauritania]], leading Senegal to qualify for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|World Cup 2026]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Senegal Defeats Mauritania and Qualifies for the 2026 World Cup with a Sadio Mané Double | url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/articles/senegal-defeats-mauritania-and-qualifies-for-the-2026-world-cup-with-a-sadio-man%C3%A9-double-2025-10-14 |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=14 October 2025 }}</ref> Later that year, he was called up for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Senegal take fitness gamble as Thiaw names injured trio in AFCON squad|url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/senegal-take-fitness-gamble-as-thiaw-names-injured-trio-in-afcon-squad/|website=CAFOnline.com|date=14 December 2025|access-date=14 December 2025}}</ref>

On 14 January 2026, Mané's goal sealed a 1–0 semi-final win against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] in the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/mane-the-hero-as-senegal-edge-egypt-to-reach-totalenergies-caf-afcon-2025-final/ |title=Mané the hero as Senegal edge Egypt to reach TotalEnergies CAF AFCON 2025 Final |publisher=CAF Online |date=14 January 2026 }}</ref> On 18 January, Senegal eventually managed to defeat host nation [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] 1–0 after extra time in the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations final|final]], with Mané lifting the trophy as captain of his nation and earning the tournament’s best player award.<ref>{{cite web |date=19 January 2026 |title=Senegal beat Morocco thanks to Gueye strike in extraordinary AFCON 2025 final: Live updates and reaction |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/senegal-vs-morocco-afcon-2025-final-score-result/DQtU75DqxAoW/ |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=18 January 2026 |title=AFCON 2025: Sadio Mane wins best player - All awards at a glance- complete list |url=https://www.olympics.com/en/news/afcon-2025-sadio-mane-wins-best-player-all-awards-at-a-glance-complete-list |publisher=Olympics.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stevens |first1=Rob |last2=Coates |first2=Charlotte |date=18 January 2026 |title='An ambassador for African football' - Mané is Senegal's Afcon hero |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/clynjj2ngy8o |access-date=19 January 2026 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>

== Player profile ==
[[File:Spartak Moscow VS. Liverpool (9).jpg|thumb|Mané in action for Liverpool during the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League|2017-18 UEFA Champions League]] campaign.]]
Mané was described as a complete player who plays with "high levels of intensity and concentration" by former Liverpool teammate [[Fabinho (footballer, born 1993)|Fabinho]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-sa/news/mane-is-a-complete-player-makes-liverpool-tick-fabinho/rumcckf0xh9g1jq2mrl6a93xm|title=Liverpool news: 'Sadio Mané is a complete player & makes Reds tick' – Fabinho salutes 'great' Anfield colleague|last=Burton|first=Chris|date=14 June 2019|website=Goal.com|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> Former Liverpool defender [[Jamie Carragher]] called Mané a "world-class winger", comparing him to the likes of former Liverpool player [[John Barnes (footballer)|John Barnes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/world-class-mane-is-a-machine-says-carragher/2le5638cd63n1bp7amg00oj3x|title='World-class' Mané is a machine, says former Liverpool man Carragher|date=13 October 2019|website=Goal.com|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> He was also compared to [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] by former Ajax defender [[Danny Blind]], who praised him for his ability to score with either foot and headers, along with making "astonishing" sprints.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/dutch-legend-thinks-liverpools-sadio-17384044|title=Dutch legend thinks one Liverpool star can become new Ronaldo|last=O'Neill|first=Caoimhe|date=8 December 2019|newspaper=Liverpool Echo|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref>

A versatile forward, Mané is a prolific goalscorer, whose main traits are his finishing, speed, technique, and trickery in possession, as well as his decision-making, tactical awareness, creativity, agility, balance, control, touch on the ball, and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] skills.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/liverpools-sadio-mane-speeds-up-in-the-race-to-be-among-the/1av6te8eir9501tr8vxckxai5i |title=Mane speeds up in race to be among Premier League's best |website=Goal.com |last1=Reddy |first1=Melissa |date=27 August 2017 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref name="rumours">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2818029-sadio-mane-happy-at-liverpool-says-real-madrid-rumours-didnt-interest-him |title=Sadio Mane Happy at Liverpool, Says Real Madrid Rumours Didn't Interest Him |website=Bleacher Report |last1=Jones |first1=Matt |date=28 January 2019 |access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name="quiet kid">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2018/06/08/sadio-mane-was-the-quiet-kid-with-the-superstar-talent/35833843/ |title=Sadio Mane was the 'quiet kid' with the superstar talent |website=USA Today |date=8 June 2018 |access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name="terrifying">{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpool.com/liverpool-fc-news/features/liverpool-sadio-mane-jurgen-klopp-17742762 |title=Sadio Mané is doing something Neymar and Hazard aren't, making him a uniquely terrifying fighter |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last1=Austin |first1=Daniel |date=14 February 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-utd-liverpool-sadio-mane-17818963 |title=Man Utd boss Solskjaer names the Club Brugge player who reminds him of Liverpool FC star Sadio Mane |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |last1=Marshall |first1=Tyrone |date=26 February 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref> He has also drawn praise in the media for his intelligent play, passing, and his ability to get into good positions, from which he can score goals or create chances for teammates.<ref name="rumours"/><ref name="quiet kid"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpool.com/liverpool-fc-news/features/sadio-mane-liverpool-champions-league-17399995 |title=Sadio Mané has added a new facet to his game, eliminating his only remaining blind spot |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last1=Rabinowitz |first1=Joel |date=11 December 2019 |access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/sadio-mane-stars-as-creator-and-finisher-as-liverpool-look-short-/5ljdcf8sgbbc1fim2q7qmrl90 |title=Sadio Mane stars as creator and finisher as Liverpool look short of guile again |website=Goal.com |last1=Reddy |first1=Melissa |date=19 August 2017 |access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref> Known for his quiet and timid personality, his ability to cope with pressure has also been highlighted as one of his main strengths.<ref name="quiet kid"/> Beyond his offensive, technical, and creative qualities, his high defensive work-rate has also been noted by pundits, as well as his ability in the air, despite his modest stature of {{convert|1.75|m|ftin|abbr=on}}.<ref name="terrifying"/> Mané usually plays as a winger on the left flank, a position which allows him to cut into the centre and shoot on goal with his stronger, right foot.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpool.com/schedule/liverpool-sadio-mane-norwich-goal-17756340 |title=Sadio Mané has become Liverpool's Arjen Robben, by doing the same in a totally opposite way |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |last1=Austin |first1=Daniel |date=16 February 2020 |access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> During the [[2021–22 Liverpool F.C. season|2021–22 season]], with the signing of [[Luis Díaz (footballer, born 1997)|Luis Díaz]], Mané began playing more as a central striker and flourished in that role.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pearce |first1=James |title=Diaz's arrival has helped give outstanding Mane a new lease of life |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3254593/2022/04/17/diaz-arrival-helped-give-outstanding-mane-new-lease-life-liverpool/ |website=The Athletic |date=13 May 2022 |access-date=27 May 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pearce |first1=James |title=New deal for 'machine' Mane should be high on Liverpool's to-do list |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3305156/2022/05/11/sadio-manes-new-contract-should-be-a-priority-for-liverpool-after-keeping-title-hopes-alive/ |website=The Athletic |date=13 May 2022 |access-date=27 May 2022}}</ref> In 2022, Mané was cited by [[Kyle Walker]] as one of the toughest opponents he has ever faced in his career.<ref>{{cite web |title= Kyle Walker names Mane as 'toughest opponent' over Mbappe and Neymar |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J1gBMg_A9Ww |website=YouTube | date=7 December 2022 |access-date=19 March 2023}}</ref>

== Community and philanthropy ==
In 2019, Mané donated £250,000 (${{Formatnum:{{To USD|250000|GBR|year=2019|r=0}}}}; €{{Formatnum:{{To EUR|250000|GBR|year=2019|r=0}}}}) to build a school in his home town of Bambali, Senegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/10/17/soccer/1571297668_422970.html|title=Sadio Mané: "Why would I want 10 Ferraris? How would that help me or the world?"|publisher=sa.com|date=17 October 2019}}</ref> In March 2020, Mané donated £41,000 (${{Formatnum:{{To USD|41000|GBR|year=2020|r=0}}}}; €{{Formatnum:{{To EUR|41000|GBR|year=2020|r=0}}}}) to the national committee fighting [[COVID-19 pandemic in Senegal|COVID-19 in Senegal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bigissue.com/news/activism/all-the-things-afcon-winner-sadio-mane-has-done-for-charity/|title=All the amazing things Sadio Mané has done for charity|publisher=Big Issue|date=14 September 2022}}</ref> In 2021, he donated £500,000 (${{Formatnum:{{To USD|500000|GBR|r=0}}}}; €{{Formatnum:{{To EUR|500000|GBR|r=0}}}}) towards the construction of a hospital in Bambali.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/22/football/sadio-mane-funds-hometown-hospital-spt-intl/index.html|title=Sadio Mane donates $693,000 to fund hospital in his hometown in Senegal|publisher=CNN|date=22 June 2021}}</ref> In addition, he has also financed the building of a petrol station and a post office for his local community, supplying the school with free laptops and internet from the [[4G]] internet service he financed in the village. In total, he has spent more than £700,000 (${{Formatnum:{{To USD|700000|GBR|r=0}}}}; €{{Formatnum:{{To EUR|700000|GBR|r=0}}}}) on these upgrades. In addition, he commissioned a €70-a-month [[stipend]] to each family in his 2,000-person hometown.<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 June 2022 |title=Mane uses fortune to fund hospitals and build schools - he's football's nice guy |url=https://talksport.com/football/1134288/sadio-mane-salary-village-charity-bayern-contract-liverpool/ |access-date=23 February 2023 |website=talkSPORT |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=H |first=Miqdad |title=Sadio Mane was born in a very small village in Senegal – we'll tell you more about our star's birthplace in 10 key things |url=https://tribuna.com/en/news/liverpoolfc-2021-01-19-sadio-mane-was-born-in-a-very-small-in-senegal-well-tell-you-more-about-our-stars-birthpl/ |access-date=23 February 2023 |website=Tribuna.com |date=19 January 2021 |language=en}}</ref> This is roughly equivalent to a month's wage for a Senegalese citizen on a [[minimum wage]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Senegal - Minimum wages 2022 {{!}} countryeconomy.com |url=https://countryeconomy.com/national-minimum-wage/senegal |access-date=23 February 2023 |website=countryeconomy.com |language=en}}</ref>

Mané is also an ambassador for [[Right To Play]], an international non-profit organization with a mission to empower vulnerable children. He has collaborated with the non-profit to provide equality and empowerment to young girls and [[women in Senegal]], raising "awareness of the importance for both girls and boys to be able to access sport and education opportunities".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.righttoplay.org.uk/en-uk/news/empowering-girls-through-sport-and-play-in-senegal/|title=Empowering girls through sport and play in Senegal | access-date= 29 January 2022 |publisher=Right to Play}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Whilst at Liverpool, Mané resided in [[Allerton, Liverpool|Allerton]], Liverpool, and has been burgled twice, once in November 2017 and again in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Burglars target homes of Liverpool's Mané and Lovren |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-merseyside-41848346 |access-date=20 February 2019 |website=BBC News |date=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sadio Mané: Liverpool forward's house burgled during Champions League match |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/47309681 |access-date=20 February 2019 |website=BBC Sport |date=20 February 2019}}</ref> He is a practising [[Muslim]] and occasionally is seen making [[Dua|du'a]] before the start of each match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sadio Mané: The little man with a big heart who has fuelled Liverpool's title challenge |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/sadio-mane-little-man-big-12348124 |first=James|last=Pearce |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=20 December 2016 |access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref>

He was appointed a [[National Order of the Lion|Grand Officer of the National Order of the Lion]] by [[President of Senegal]] [[Macky Sall]] following the nation's victory at the 2021 Africa Cup of Nations.<ref name= "reuters">{{cite web |title=Cash prizes, real estate, and highest honours as Senegal celebrates Nations Cup heroes |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/cash-prizes-real-estate-highest-honours-senegal-celebrates-nations-cup-heroes-2022-02-08/ |website=[[Reuters]] |access-date=28 March 2023 |date=8 February 2022}}</ref>

He married Aisha Tamba, who is 13 years younger than him, on 7 January 2024 through an [[Islam|Islamic rite]]. At the time of their marriage, he was 31 and she was 18 years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/tikitakas/sadio-mane-se-casa-con-su-pareja-de-18-anos-n/|title=Sadio Mané se casa con su pareja de 18 años|publisher=As.com|language=Spanish|date=9 January 2024|access-date=9 January 2024}}</ref> They had reportedly met more than two years before.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/father-sadio-mane-wife-aisha-timba-confirms-daughter-age-traditional-arranged-marriage-al-nassr-star/blt17048784ee0a20e0|title=Father of Sadio Mane's wife Aisha Timba confirms daughter's age & admits to traditional arranged marriage for Al-Nassr star|last=Burton|first=Chris|work=Goal.com|language=EN|date=11 January 2024|access-date=13 January 2024}}</ref>

